<Docs title="Training" description="Benchmark real models and train a calibrated capability router.">
  <p class="eyebrow">Training &amp; evaluation</p>
  <h1>Difficulty labels are not ground truth.</h1>
  <p class="lead">A prompt “looks hard” is not a useful target. Run the task through every candidate model, score the outputs, and label it with the cheapest tier that actually passes.</p>

  <div class="callout"><p>The included seed dataset is a smoke test. Its current nine-row holdout is intentionally reported honestly and is not suitable for production.</p></div>

  <h2>Benchmark every tier</h2>
  <p>Use the provider-backed runner when your models are reachable through an OpenAI-compatible chat completions API.</p>
  <div class="code-window"><div class="code-bar"><i></i><i></i><i></i>terminal</div><pre><code>cp router.example.json router.json
cp examples/benchmark.config.example.json benchmark.config.json
cp examples/benchmark_prompts.example.jsonl benchmark_prompts.jsonl

OPENAI_API_KEY=... PYTHONPATH=src python3 examples/benchmark_pipeline.py \
  --config benchmark.config.json</code></pre></div>

  <p>Set the three model IDs in <code>router.json</code>, then point <code>benchmark.config.json</code> at your prompt file and output path.</p>
  <div class="code-window"><div class="code-bar"><i></i><i></i><i></i>benchmark.config.json</div><pre><code>&#123;
  <span class="token-string">"router_config"</span>: <span class="token-string">"router.json"</span>,
  <span class="token-string">"prompts"</span>: <span class="token-string">"benchmark_prompts.jsonl"</span>,
  <span class="token-string">"output"</span>: <span class="token-string">"data/benchmark.jsonl"</span>,
  <span class="token-string">"provider"</span>: &#123;
    <span class="token-string">"base_url"</span>: <span class="token-string">"https://api.openai.com/v1"</span>,
    <span class="token-string">"api_key_env"</span>: <span class="token-string">"OPENAI_API_KEY"</span>
  &#125;,
  <span class="token-string">"judge"</span>: &#123; <span class="token-string">"model"</span>: <span class="token-string">"gpt-4.1-mini"</span> &#125;
&#125;</code></pre></div>

  <p>Each prompt row supplies the task, the judge reference or rubric, and an optional group for leakage-safe splitting.</p>
  <div class="code-window"><div class="code-bar"><i></i><i></i><i></i>benchmark_prompts.jsonl</div><pre><code>&#123;<span class="token-string">"prompt"</span>:<span class="token-string">"Implement and test an API rate limiter."</span>,<span class="token-string">"reference"</span>:<span class="token-string">"Must include token bucket logic, concurrency safety, and tests."</span>,<span class="token-string">"group"</span>:<span class="token-string">"rate-limit-1"</span>&#125;</code></pre></div>

  <h2>What gets recorded</h2>
  <ul><li>A normalized 0–1 score for low, medium, and high.</li><li>Per-tier latency and provider failure details.</li><li>Task group and weight for leakage-safe splitting.</li><li>The original prompt, ready for the training loader.</li></ul>

  <h2>Train and calibrate</h2>
  <div class="code-window"><div class="code-bar"><i></i><i></i><i></i>terminal</div><pre><code>smol-router train data/benchmark.jsonl \
    --acceptable-score 0.8 \
    --output model.json

smol-router evaluate data/locked-test.jsonl --model model.json</code></pre></div>
  <p>Training uses weighted softmax regression over deterministic hashed features, then fits scalar temperature on held-out examples. Related task groups never cross the automatic split.</p>

  <h2>Read the right metrics</h2>
  <ul><li><strong>Under-route rate:</strong> how often the policy selected an incapable tier.</li><li><strong>Mean shortfall:</strong> how many capability levels were missed.</li><li><strong>Regret:</strong> realized cost compared with the cheapest sufficient model.</li><li><strong>Calibration:</strong> log loss and Brier score for probability quality.</li><li><strong>Savings:</strong> selected cost compared with always choosing high.</li></ul>

  <h2>Production loop</h2>
  <ol><li>Sample representative prompts from real traffic.</li><li>Score all candidate models with task-specific checks or validated review.</li><li>Lock an untouched test set and define a maximum under-route rate.</li><li>Tune costs and penalties from actual price, latency, and failure impact.</li><li>Re-benchmark whenever an underlying model changes.</li></ol>
</Docs>
